docs.abstract: “Defund the police” and “cancel rent” aren’t reforms, but paths to revolution.
docs.snippet: “Defund the police” and “cancel rent” aren’t reforms, but paths to revolution.
docs.lead_paragraph: The uprisings in response to the killing of George Floyd are far different from anything that has come before. Not just because they may be the largest in our history, or that seven weeks in, people are still in the streets (even if the news media has largely moved on). But also because, for the last few years, organizers have been thinking boldly.

headline.main: The Left Is Remaking the World

docs.lead_paragraph: Early last month, amid protests against police violence in the wake of the George Floyd killing, the pink brick wall surrounding the cemetery of the original St. Patrick’s Cathedral in NoLIta was spray-painted with graffiti, while a storm window protecting one of the church’s soaring stained-glass windows was broken.

headline.main: At Old St. Pat’s, a History of Defiance

docs.abstract: This 1992 animated movie about Black children running into trouble at a theme park is meant to be a comedy. But for one viewer, it no longer seems so funny.
docs.snippet: This 1992 animated movie about Black children running into trouble at a theme park is meant to be a comedy. But for one viewer, it no longer seems so funny.
docs.lead_paragraph: “The Boondocks,” “Atlanta,” “black-ish,” “Dear White People,” “Sorry to Bother You” — there are a few shows and movies that have dared to use comedy to address the grim state of Black people in America. But lately, I’ve been thinking about a movie I hadn’t seen in more than 20 years: “Bébé’s Kids.” This animated Black comedy explicitly spoke about police brutality and our broken judicial system years before the first utterance of “Black Lives Matter.”

headline.main: ‘Bébé’s Kids’ Shared a Lesson About Racial Injustice
headline.print_headline: On Second Thought, a Movie Isn’t So Funny
